    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/statistical-test-comparison/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have designed methylKit to implement two main methods for determining differential methylation across all regions: logistic regression and Fisher's exact test... Following the differential methylation test and calculation of P-values, methylKit will use the sliding linear model (SLIM) method to correct P-values to q-values [31], which corrects for the problem of multiple hypothesis testing [32,33]. However, we also implemented the standard false discovery rate (FDR)-based method (Benjamini-Hochberg) as an option for P-value correction, which is faster but more conservative.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes q-value correction methods (SLIM and Benjamini-Hochberg) and multiple testing correction, but does NOT explicitly discuss overdispersion correction (overdispersion='MN' parameter) or variance adjustment for overdispersion. The paper mentions logistic regression and Fisher's exact test but does not compare corrected vs. uncorrected analyses with overdispersion parameters. The research question assumes overdispersion correction functionality that is not documented in the provided passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2012-13-10-r87",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "statistical-test-comparison",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Compare statistical test stringency and multiple-testing correction outcomes (q-value distributions, test type, variance adjustment) between corrected and uncorrected differential methylation analyses to verify that overdispersion correction produces more conservative significanc",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:20:34.487998+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/statistical-test-comparison/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Here, we describe an R package, methylKit, that rapidly analyzes genome-wide cytosine epigenetic profiles from high-throughput methylation and hydroxymethylation sequencing experiments. methylKit includes functions for clustering, sample quality visualization, differential methylation analysis and annotation features... methylKit can read DNA methylation information from a text file and also from alignment files (for example, SAM files)... and carry out operations such as differential methylation analysis, sample clustering and annotation, and visualization of DNA methylation events",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms methylKit provides differential methylation analysis and methylBase objects. However, the paper does NOT mention calculateDiffMeth(), dataSim() functions, or overdispersion correction parameters by name. The paper describes logistic regression and Fisher's exact test but does not document tunable overdispersion correction as a feature.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-gb-2012-13-10-r87",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "statistical-test-comparison",
